               <p>761. <persName id="def1-761-18630511" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-761-18630511" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-761-18630511" type="age" value="27"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-761-18630511" type="surname" value="BROWN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-761-18630511" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN BROWN</hi> (27)</persName>, and <persName id="def2-761-18630511" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-761-18630511" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-761-18630511" type="age" value="22"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-761-18630511" type="surname" value="KEMBLE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-761-18630511" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">CHARLES KEMBLE</hi>
                  </persName> (22), <rs id="t18630511-761-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18630511-761-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18630511-761-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="theftFromPlace"></interp>Stealing 3 rings, value 7<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., the property of <persName id="t18630511-name-662" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18630511-name-662" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18630511-name-662" type="surname" value="BLACK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18630511-name-662" type="given" value="JOHN TRAFALGAR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18630511-name-662" type="occupation" value="tutor"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18630511-761-offence-1 t18630511-name-662"></join>John Trafalgar Black</persName>, in his dwelling-house.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PALMER</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MARIAN BLACK</hi>. I am the wife of John Trafalgar Black, a tutor, of 4, Hamilton-place, Brixton-road—on 27th April, the prisoners came—my servant let them into the dining-room, and then into the drawing-room—I followed them, and asked them what apartment they wanted—they said a dewing-room floor and two bedrooms—they told me they were professional singers, engaged at different houses, and that they kept a "trap"—I showed them the drawing-room floor; there was no property of mine them—the servant then took them to this second-floor—my bedroom is on that floor, Over the drawing-room—I heard some one overhead, in my room—the servant then brought them down—they said there was another professional singer, and wished to know what other bedroom I could let them have—knowing that they had been in my room, I suspected them, and directed my servant to show her bedroom, to give me time—they went up stairs again, and I ran up to my bedroom, and missed three rings, which I had left on the looking-glass, worth 6<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. or 7<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I then came down, and waited at the drawing-room door until the prisoners came down—I went into the ball before them—they said the apartment would suit them very well—I said, "I wish to speak to you; step into the dining-room for a minute,"—they said their time was up, and they must go—I said, "I cannot allow you to go until you have given me the three rings which you have taken from my bedroom"—I put the chain on the front door—they were then in the hall, coming towards the door—I stood before them, and would not let them pass—they said, "Oh, dear no, madam; the very idea of such a thing! we are too respectable; we have never been guilty of such a thing"—I said, "You have them"—there was a life-preserver hanging on the folding-door between the front and back room; Kemble took it off the door—I said, "You had better give me up the rings; what do you intend doing f you will be trans<lb></lb>ported; if you have no fear of man, have you no fear of God? if yon give me up the rings, I will release you"—there was a friend of nine down Stairs—I called him up—as he was coming up, the prisoners said, "If you</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186305110188"></xptr>
               <p>look round the room, you will find your property"—I had seen Brown put something on the sofa, and I said, "I saw where you put them"—he then took the three rings between his thumb and finger, brought them to me, and said, "Now you have got your property, you will allow us to go"—I said, "No"—I thought I saw the life-preserver in one of the prisoners' pocket—it had been lying on the table when my friend came up, and one of them took it off—they refused to give up the rings until the police were at the door.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DICKIE</hi>. (<hi rend="italic">For Brown</hi>) <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you sent for a policeman? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, I had sent my servant, and heard her putting the key in the door—the moment they heard footsteps, Brown dropped the rings—the door was opened by my friend, and there were the servant and two policemen.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SMITH</hi>. (<hi rend="italic">For Kamble</hi>). <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When they came to the house, I suppose you thought them respectable? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I had my doubts—I let my servant show them over the premises instead of going with them—there was no property in the bed-room which the servant showed them—her room is on the third floor, and mine is on the second floor—Kemble was the one that took the life-preserver—there was no attempt to strike me—I said if they gave up the rings I would let them go, because I thought it would give me time to send for a policeman—perhape when I made that promise I had the intention of breaking it—I intended to see whether they had robbed me of my property—when you have thieves in the house you do the best you can.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Dickie. Q.</hi> Did yon ever say anything about the life-preserver before to<lb></lb>day? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I did to the policeman—I was not asked about it before the Magis<lb></lb>trate—it was taken off the door in my presence—it was not attempted to be used—I am certain I saw the rings when last in my room—I had taken them off to wash my hands.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PALMER</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you any other motive in making the promise but the laudable strategy of gaining time? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18630511-name-663" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18630511-name-663" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18630511-name-663" type="surname" value="LAKE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18630511-name-663" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM LAKE</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Policeman, P</hi> 264). I was called, and look the prisoners at Hamilton-place—they made no statement—they were given in charge for stealing the rings—they gave a false address—there was another constable.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Kemble received a good character.</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18630511-761-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
